Text Mining Kickstarter Projects

Overview

Kickstarter is an American public-benefit corporation based in Brooklyn, New York, that maintains a global crowd funding platform focused on creativity. The companys stated mission is to help bring creative projects to life.

<src=>

Kickstarter has reportedly received almost $5 billion in pledges from 17.6 million backers to fund 180,000 creative projects, such as films, music, stage shows, comics, journalism, video games, technology and food-related projects.

Data

The dataset for this assignment is taken from webroboto.io s repository. They developed a scrapper robot that crawls all Kickstarter projects monthly since 2009. We will just take data from the most recent crawl on 2020-02-13.

Tasks for the Assignment

1. Identifying Successful Projects

a) Success by Category

There are several ways to identify success of a project:
- State (state): Whether a campaign was successful or not.
- Pledged Amount (pledged)
- Achievement Ratio: Create a variable achievement_ratio by calculating the percentage of the original monetary goal reached by the actual amount pledged (that is pledged\goal *100).
- Number of backers (backers_count)
- How quickly the goal was reached (difference between launched_at and state_changed_at) for those campaigns that were successful.

Use one or more of these measures to visually summarize which categories were most successful in attracting funding on kickstarter. Briefly summarize your findings.

New columns

# What %of money was raised as a factor of goal set
data$achievement_ratio <- (data$pledged / data$goal) * 100

# How quickly the goal was reached
data$weeks_to_goal <-
  as.duration(ymd(data$state_changed_at) - ymd(data$launched_at)) / dweeks(1)

# There is one entry for 1969 this doesn't look right given that kickstarter was itself founded in 2009.
# Removing this one entry from the data
data <- data %>%
  filter(launched_at != "1969-12-31")

3. Sentiment

Now, lets check whether the use of positive / negative words or specific emotions helps a project to be successful.

a) Stay positive

Calculate the tone of each text based on the positive and negative words that are being used. You can rely on the Hu & Liu dictionary provided in lecture or use the Bing dictionary contained in the tidytext package (tidytext::sentiments). Visualize the relationship between tone of the document and success. Briefly comment.

pos <- read.table("dictionaries/positive-words.txt", as.is = T)
neg <- read.table("dictionaries/negative-words.txt", as.is = T)

sentiment <- function(words = c("really great good stuff bad")) {
  require(quanteda)
  tok <- quanteda::tokens(words)
  pos.count <- sum(tok[[1]] %in% pos[, 1])
  neg.count <- sum(tok[[1]] %in% neg[, 1])
  out <- (pos.count - neg.count) / (pos.count + neg.count)
  return(out)
}
suc_copy <- suc
unsuc_copy <- unsuc
suc_copy$senti <- map_dbl(suc_copy$text, sentiment)
unsuc_copy$senti <- map_dbl(unsuc_copy$text, sentiment)

suc_temp <- data.frame(cbind(suc_copy$senti, unsuc_copy$senti))
ggplot(suc_temp) +
  geom_jitter(aes(x = "success", y = suc_temp$X1)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(x = "unsuccessful", y = suc_temp$X2), color = "red") +
  geom_point(
    aes(x = "success", y = mean(suc_temp$X1, na.rm = TRUE)),
    color = "black",
    shape = 4,
    size = 5
  ) +
  geom_text(
  aes(x = "success", y = mean(suc_temp$X1, na.rm = TRUE) + 0.1, label = round(mean(suc_temp$X1, na.rm = TRUE), digits = 2)), size = 3, vjust = -0.3) +
  geom_point(
    aes(x = "unsuccessful", y = mean(suc_temp$X2, na.rm = TRUE)),
    color = "black",
    shape = 4,
    size = 5
  ) +
  geom_text(
  aes(x = "unsuccessful", y = mean(suc_temp$X2, na.rm = TRUE) + 0.1, label = round(mean(suc_temp$X2, na.rm = TRUE), digits = 2)), size = 3, vjust = -0.3) +
  scale_color_gradient() +
  labs(title = "Range of sentiment",
       subtitle = "Mention of positive and negative words in blurbs",
       caption = "source: https://webrobots.io/kickstarter-datasets/", parse = TRUE) +
  xlab(NULL) + ylab("Negative / Positive")

There doesnt seem to be much difference when it comes to only positive and negative emotions. Unsuccessful blurbs are ever so slightly more positive than successful blurbs.

b) Positive vs negative

Segregate all 2,000 blurbs into positive and negative texts based on their polarity score calculated in step (a). Now, collapse the positive and negative texts into two larger documents. Create a document-term-matrix based on this collapsed set of two documents. Generate a comparison cloud showing the most-frequent positive and negative words.

pos <- rbind((suc_copy %>%
                filter(senti > 0) %>%
                select(text)),
             (unsuc_copy %>%
                filter(senti > 0) %>%
                select(text)))

neg <- rbind((suc_copy %>%
                filter(senti < 0) %>%
                select(text)),
             (unsuc_copy %>%
                filter(senti < 0) %>%
                select(text)))

pos <- paste0(pos$text, collapse = " ")

neg <- paste0(neg$text, collapse = " ")

doc_id <- c("pos", "neg")

# creating a unified dataframe with one column textid, second column blurbs
posneg <-
  data.frame(doc_id,
             text = c(pos, neg),
             stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

posneg_df <- DataframeSource(posneg)

posneg_corpus <- VCorpus(posneg_df)

posneg_clean <- clean_corpus(posneg_corpus)

posneg_tdm <- TermDocumentMatrix(posneg_clean)

posneg_m <- as.matrix(posneg_tdm)
# Create comparison cloud
comparison.cloud(posneg_m, colors = c("orange", "blue"), 
                 scale=c(0.1,2), title.size= 1, 
                 max.words = 100)

A picture is worth 200 words. Here is collection of 100 most-frequent positive and negative words that have been used in the subset of 2000 blurbs.

Some of the positive words are obvious like awesome, beautiful, provide, perfect.

Some words that have been categorized as negative are confusing like - friends, animals, edition, series, ginger.

More analysis needs to be done as to why has the dictionary classified these words as negative.

c) Get in their mind

Now, use the NRC Word-Emotion Association Lexicon in the tidytext package to identify a larger set of emotions (anger, anticipation, disgust, fear, joy, sadness, surprise, trust). Again, visualize the relationship between the use of words from these categories and success. What is your finding?

all_m_df <- as.data.frame(all_m)

all_m_df$word = rownames(all_m_df)

all_senti <- inner_join(all_m_df, get_sentiments("nrc"), by = "word")
all_senti %>%
  group_by(sentiment) %>%
  summarise(sum_suc_senti = sum(`1`),
            sum_unsuc_senti = sum(`2`)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(reorder(sentiment, sum_suc_senti), y = sum_suc_senti, color = "Successful")) +
  geom_point(aes(sentiment, sum_unsuc_senti, color = "Unsuccessful")) +
  labs(title = "Larger set of emotions",
       subtitle = "Analysing 2000 project blurbs for range of emotions",
       caption = "source: https://webrobots.io/kickstarter-datasets/", parse = TRUE) +
  xlab(NULL) + ylab("Number of words") +
  coord_flip()

Unsuccessful projects have more positive, trust, joy, anticipation feelings.

And when it comes to negative emotions like- sadness, fear, anger, disgust both blurbs have almost same number of words.

This graph seems to imply that maybe projects that oversell positivity are not liked much by the Kickstarter pledgers.
